    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Charleston</placeName>
                <date>23 Aug 1852</date>
            </p>
            <p>My dear <addressee>Mr Leeser</addressee>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I have just read in the last Asmoneon<lb/> (handed me by a friend)
                    <persName>Mr A Breslaws</persName> attack upon<lb/> you; I pray you not to <hi
                    rend="underline">notice</hi> or <hi rend="underline">advert to it</hi> in<lb/>
                any manner, the letter bears the evidence and impress<lb/> of a man of a low bred
                and loose character—it is in<lb/> truth a “scurrilous thing”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">—”Revocate animos, moestumque timorem<lb/>
                    mittite.—<persName>Virgil</persName> Aeneid;—</p>
            <p><persName>Pericles</persName> is made to utter the following sentences<lb/> and I
                give them to you in the language of his historian
                    <persName><sic>Thucidides</sic></persName></p>
            <quote>“ To be censured and maligned for a <hi rend="underline">time</hi> hath been
                the<lb/> fate of <hi rend="underline">all those</hi> whose <hi rend="underline"
                    >merit</hi> hath <hi rend="underline">raised them above the common</hi><lb/>
                level, but <hi rend="underline">wise</hi> and <hi rend="underline">judicious</hi> is
                the <hi rend="underline">man</hi> who enjoying the<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">superiority, dispiseth the envy.</hi>”</quote>
            <p rend="indent(1)">This man <persName>M H Breslaw</persName>, would like no better<lb/>
                opportunity than to be made famous at <hi rend="underline">your
                    <sic>expensce</sic></hi>.<lb/> Trust him, <persName>Mr Lyon</persName>, and his
                    <sic>sattellites</sic> with the supreme<lb/> contempt they deserved= I
                    <del>enclose</del> transcribe for you a public notice which<lb/> I remember to
                have read some time ago. I have just looked for and<lb/> found it.
                    <placeName>London</placeName> Jewish Chronicle, <date>July 14-21-28</date>
                <date>Aug 4.<lb/> 11-25<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date>. “public notice.” It is <hi
                    rend="underline">most particularly requested</hi><lb/> that <hi rend="underline"
                    >no money</hi> be paid to <persName>Mr <hi rend="underline">M H
                    Bresslaw</hi></persName>, on account<lb/> of the Jewish Chronicle, he having <hi
                    rend="underline">long</hi> ceased to be in the<lb/> employment of the
                proprietor, <persName>Joseph Mitchelo</persName>”</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">This must mean something—therefore a man</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>who has been publicly <sic>advertized</sic>
                <add>for more than two months consecutively</add> for some “delinquency” as the<lb/>
                must suppose—is no fit person for <persName>Isaac Leeser</persName> to<lb/> contend
                or enter into a controversy with under <hi rend="underline">no</hi>
                circumstances<lb/> whatever. I wrote you when you invited the anonymous<lb/>
                correspondent to come forward and when your article appeared<lb/> on the subject
                that I thought it impolitic, I feared the<lb/> result—and my fear, has been
                realized.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Now my good friend=all this comes form c<hi rend="underline"
                    >ontend</hi>ing<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">about Trifles—</hi>and the note I sent you to be affixed<lb/>
                to my article comes in admirably—What do the public<lb/> or the readers of the
                Occident care, about who gives a <hi rend="underline">Get</hi><lb/> or <hi
                    rend="underline">How</hi> it is given,—whether <persName>Mr Nuerbaum</persName>
                marries<lb/> on Honer—or on <date>Kipur Day</date>.—let all such things<lb/> stand
                on their own merits, and for the future take<lb/> an enlarged view of these <hi
                    rend="underline">Trifles</hi> and allow, <persName>Mr Levin<lb/>
                    Abrahams</persName> and his set to become <hi rend="underline">Trifles if
                    they</hi> will,<lb/> do you not see that there is no <hi rend="underline"
                    >Religion</hi> in it</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You have translated and given us “<placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>”
                Why<lb/> not <add>advocate</add>
                <persName>Mendelsons</persName> views,—<sic>Thise</sic> is a <hi rend="underline"
                    >Harbor</hi> to be reached<lb/> The good ship has been tossed about on the seas
                    <add>of <placeName>Biscbay</placeName> &amp; superstition</add> for<lb/> over
                one Hundred years <add>on American Seas</add> and no land in sight yet.<lb/>
                <del>It is</del> is it not time to consult the charts given us<lb/> by
                    <persName>Moses</persName> &amp; the Prophets and by whether, we may not<lb/> be
                able to reach the much desired Haven of Religion<lb/> look at the numberless young
                men. (the best sailors) that<lb/> have deserted the ship by escaping over the side, <del>
                    <add>?</add>
                </del> (intermanagers)<lb/> preferring to swim to some shore rather than remain on
                board<lb/> where there is so much contention and strife about things<lb/> of no
                consequence that they became disgusted—is it not</p>
            <pb n="2R"/>
            <p>imperatively demanded that we should let our children<lb/> know that there is a true
                course to be steered and<lb/> that, our religion is not one of <hi rend="underline"
                    >Contention</hi> but of peace<lb/> and good will to all men,</p>
            <p>It is all nonsense to expect to govern men by a code<lb/> of Laws which their own <hi
                    rend="underline">actions</hi> plainly speak that they do<lb/> not
                    <sic>recognized</sic> the authority of the men who made them and will not<lb/>
                be governed except by &amp; with their <hi rend="underline">own consent</hi>.—</p>
            <p>and. yet. these people <add>who neither practice Biblical Laws &amp;
                        orders<add>?</add> or</add> make a great noise when attacked<lb/> guided by
                circumstances hazards an opinion <add>on a Rabbinic affair</add> which
                conflicts<lb/> with the opinion of another, perhaps less qualified to Judge<lb/> on
                the case, you begin to feel what it is to be <hi rend="underline">crushed</hi><lb/>
                and h<add>?</add>ed down without mercy for <hi rend="underline">a
                Trifle</hi>,—therefore<lb/> let them <add>?</add> alone for the future. And continue
                your exe<add>?</add><lb/> for the moral and religious improvement of the people<lb/>
                make them feel and <del>understand</del> know that they stand under a<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Law</hi> that they cannot exert without <hi rend="underline"
                    >Religion—</hi>when this is<lb/> achieved and the restire<add>?</add> horses are
                broken in to <del>harness</del> harness—<lb/> you can lead them or drive them on any
                road<lb/> and to any place you like.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I have written this not out of abundance of<lb/> leisure time, but
                of true affection towards you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(8)"><persName role="author">J. N. Carvalho</persName>.</p>
            <p><persName>N. Nathan</persName>. (Trustee) Son</p>
            <p><persName>Simon</persName> aged about 17 or 18 died last night}</p>
            <p>he has been in ill health for years.—</p>
            <p>a happy release for him.</p>
            <pb n="2V"/>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Editor of the Occident</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <placeName>Walnut St. near Thirteenth</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
